Microscopy showed changes in the erythrocyte shape; the control erythrocytes were discocytes (Fig. 5
), whereas increasing dendrimer or dendriplex concentrations led to changed morphology (Fig. 5, Fig. 6
). Both dendrimers at 0.4 μM induced echinocytic transformation. Many cells were shrunk and had characteristically irregular contours. For higher dendrimer concentrations, aggregates occurred but without echinocytes, the cells having regular shapes. The most striking difference between the effects of the two dendrimers was seen at 50 μM, at which erythrocytes with BDBR0011 formed huge aggregates (~ 140 μm) whereas the NN16 dendrimer led to much smaller aggregates (~ 30 μm).
